John de Lichfield, Thomas Sherman and Thomas de Holland, Chamberlains of the Gild of the Holy Trinity, complainants, appeared against Thomas de Arnold in a plea of debt, who many times made default; and now the aforesaid John, Thomas and Thomas come in their own persons, and say that the said Thomas de Arnold owes them 5 marks of silver for the aforesaid Gild of the Holy Trinity‚ which he should have paid at the feast of the Purification of the Blessed Mary, in the 20th year of the reign of King Richard the Second, and although he had been often asked the said Thomas de Arnold refused, and to this time refuses, to pay them the aforesaid 5 marks, to the damage of the aforesaid John, Thomas and Thomas of 4os.‚ wherefore they enter suit, etc. And the aforesaid Thomas de Arnold comes in his own person, and defends the force and injury, ete, and says that he owes them nothing as they have above set forth against him, and this he asks may be inquired3 and the others likewise, etc.1 1296, ro. 17.
